  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. These include:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first international treaties to explicitly address money laundering. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands the scope of anti-money laundering efforts to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, not just drug trafficking.\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a law itself, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Its \"40 Recommendations\" are considered the global standard for anti-money laundering efforts. Many countries have incorporated these recommendations into their national laws.\n*   **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 and revised in 2005):** This convention focuses on measures to deprive criminals of the proceeds of their illegal activities through confiscation and other means. It also promotes international cooperation in investigations and asset recovery.\n\nThese international laws and agreements provide a framework for countries to enact their own national laws and regulations to combat money laundering. They also encourage international cooperation in investigations, asset recovery, and the sharing of information.",
